You need to fetch data, but the filters are complicated nested conditions, arrays, maybe a date range or two. GET is supposed to be the method for this. Problem is, URLs have size limits, and the second you try to shove a proper filter object into a query string, it turns into an unreadable pile of encoded garbage. So everyone does the same workaround: switch to POST. Nothing’s actually being created, but whatever, it works.
Except it doesn’t really work, not cleanly. You’re kind of lying to your own API at that point. Caches have no idea it’s safe to reuse. Proxies don’t know it’s idempotent. And six months later, some teammate has to open the controller just to figure out “wait, is this thing actually reading or writing?”
Anyway, in June 2026 the IETF finally fixed this. RFC 10008 introduces a new method called QUERY, and it’s a bigger deal than it sounds: first new standard HTTP method since PATCH landed back in 2010.
What QUERY Actually Fixes
QUERY behaves like GET in every way that matters for semantics, with one big difference: it’s built to carry a request body from day one.
Safe : it doesn’t change anything on the server
Idempotent:send it five times, get the same result five times.
Cacheable:proxies and CDNs can treat it like a GET.
Has a body:no more stuffing filters into a URL
Basically, it’s the method that should have existed the whole time you were choosing between “technically correct but limited” (GET) and “works but semantically dishonest” (POST).
What This Means If You’re on the MERN Stack
For an Express or Node backend, adopting QUERY today looks a lot like handling any custom method because right now, it kind of is one. Heads up though browsers can’t actually send QUERY through fetch yet, so don’t go rewriting your frontend fetch calls this weekend. Right now it’s mainly useful for backend-to-backend stuff, internal tools, or anywhere you control both the client and the server yourself. Here’s a simple Express example:
const express = require(‘express’);
const app = express();
app.use(express.json());
app.use(‘/api/products’, (req, res, next) => {
if (req.method === ‘QUERY’) {
return handleProductQuery(req, res);
}
next();
});
function handleProductQuery(req, res) {
const { category, priceRange, inStock } = req.body;
const results = products.filter(p => {
return (!category || p.category === category) &&
(!priceRange || (p.price >= priceRange.min && p.price <= priceRange.max)) &&
(!inStock || p.stock > 0);
});
res.json({ count: results.length, results });
}
app.listen(3000);
Should You Use It Right Now?
Honestly not in production yet. Here’s a more natural version:The spec itself is locked in, but the tooling around it is still playing catch-up. `fetch` and `XHR` can’t send a QUERY request yet — that’s on browser vendors to sort out. And framework support isn’t really there either. Don’t expect a clean `app.query()` helper in Express or an equivalent in Spring anytime soon; you’re mostly working around it manually for now.
What you should do is understand it now, so when tooling support lands later this year, you’re not starting from zero. If you’re designing a new API today, it’s worth keeping QUERY in mind as the method your search/filter endpoints will probably migrate to eventually instead of building yet another POST-that’s-secretly-a-GET.
